  "firstValueMoment": "The first meeting request lands in the user's inbox from someone who clicked their public booking link.",
  "frictionScore": 68,
  "frictionRationale": "High-band (67-100): value depends on both a calendar connection the user controls and a counterparty booking the user does not control. The flow stops at step 2 of 4, gating bookings until Google or Outlook is connected, then requires the user to distribute a link and wait for someone to schedule.",
  "recurrenceSignal": "strong",
  "durableValue": "Retention: value recurs every time someone books a meeting through the link, which happens on a per-event cadence tied to the user's work rhythm (sales calls, office hours, client intakes). The artifact that keeps producing value is the public booking link itself: once live, it sits in an email signature, a website, or a shared document, and generates bookings without the user returning to the product. The flow seeds this by showing the link (calendly.com/you/30min) and a live preview, making the distribution path obvious. A user returns to Calendly when a booking arrives (notification-driven) or when they need to adjust availability, add event types, or check their schedule. Expansion: a retained user moves to a paid plan when they need more than one active event type, want to remove Calendly branding from the booking page, need integrations beyond Google/Outlook (Salesforce, Zoom, payment collection), or want scheduling rules (buffer times, round-robin assignment, collective availability). The step 2 of 4 gate implies additional setup ahead, likely event-type limits or integration upsells, but this screen does not surface a specific upgrade trigger. The expansion path exists but is not yet visible in the flow shown.",
  "topDropOff": "The calendar connection gate. Bookings are paused until Google or Outlook is connected, and the preview shows no times until this happens. A user who wants to evaluate whether this is worth doing, or who does not use Google or Outlook as their primary calendar, cannot see a working booking page and has no proof the link will deliver value.",
  "scopeNote": "This read covers step 2 of 4 in a setup flow. The input shows event-type configuration, availability setting, and a calendar-connection gate, but not the steps before (likely account creation) or the steps after (the remaining 2 steps to reach a live booking page). The friction and value reads reflect only what is shown: the path stops at a connection gate and does not reach the moment a booking request arrives. The real frictionScore from arrival to first value is higher than 68, because this is mid-setup and the user has not yet distributed the link or received a booking.",
  "experiments": [
    {
      "hypothesis": "Let users go live without connecting a calendar, with bookings creating holds in Calendly that the user manually adds to their calendar, so they can test the booking page and receive a first request before committing to an integration.",
      "rationale": "The connection gate is the drop-off point, and it sits between the user and proof that the link works. A user who is evaluating Calendly, or who uses a calendar the product does not integrate with, cannot see a working flow and has no reason to clear the gate. Letting bookings create holds inside Calendly, with a prompt to sync after the first request arrives, gets more users to the first value moment (a booking request landing) and proves the link delivers before asking for access. The manual-add path is higher friction for repeat use, which creates a reason to connect the calendar later, when the user has seen value and wants to reduce toil.",
      "lever": "value-moment"
    },
    {
      "hypothesis": "Default the event link to public-on-creation and show it in step 1, with a 'Copy link' button and a one-line send suggestion ('Add to your email signature or send to someone'), so users distribute the link during setup rather than after it.",
      "rationale": "The first value moment depends on a counterparty booking, which depends on the user distributing the link. The flow shows the link in step 2 but does not prompt the user to send it, so most users finish setup, close the tab, and never distribute. Moving link distribution into the setup flow, with a concrete send suggestion, gets the link into circulation faster and shortens the time from setup-complete to first booking. This does not remove the calendar gate, but it seeds the counterparty action in parallel with setup, so a booking can arrive sooner after the user goes live.",
      "lever": "value-moment"
    },
    {
      "hypothesis": "After the first booking arrives, prompt the user to create a second event type for a different use case (15-minute call, 1-hour workshop, office hours), with a template picker and a 'same availability' default, so the link becomes a multi-purpose scheduling surface rather than a single-event tool.",
      "rationale": "The recurrence path is strong, but it depends on the user having a reason to return beyond waiting for bookings. A user who sets up one event type and then only opens Calendly when a booking notification arrives is retained but shallow: they are using the tool as a passive link, not as a scheduling surface. Prompting a second event type after the first booking lands, when the user has seen value and is in the product, builds a habit of returning to add capacity rather than waiting for demand. This makes the tool stickier and opens the path to paid plans, which gate multiple active event types.",
      "lever": "durable-value"
    }
  ]
}
